s testimony, and the work of Hortense Spillers, Moore shows how the logic of slavery and antiblack racism also dictates the silencing techniques of the contemporary domestic violence courtroom. By positioning testimony on contemporary domestic violence prosecution within the archive of slavery, Moore demonstrates that domestic violence and its image are haunted by black bodies, black flesh, and black freedom.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aDiscrimination in justice administrationxHistoryy19th centuryzUnited States. 0aFamily violencexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aLegal photographyzUnited States. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSlaveryxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aVictims of family violencexLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL0 cprintz978147801570340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022947?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022947/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Eng